  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Nutrition assistance for drought affected communities in Kandahar province</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In the proposed project, Save the Children will implement nutrition interventions in four priority districts of Kandahar province (Maywand, Khakrez, Shahwalikot and Zeray). Save the Children proposes to undertake the following key interventions: 
1. Establish five mobile nutrition teams to provide: Outpatient Department of Severe Acute Malnutrition (OPD-SAM) and Outpatient Department of Moderate Acute Malnutrition (OPD-MAM) services for the management of severely and moderately acute malnourished girls and boys (6-59 months) Treat acute malnourished Pregnant and Lactating Women (PLW) Promote Infant and Young Child Feeding (IYCF) practices in PLW and care givers and Treat childhood illnesses (e.g. diarrhea, acute respiratory infections and malaria) in children under the age of five (boys and girls). Out of five mobile nutrition teams, two will be established in Maywand and one will be established in each of the Khakrez, Shahwalikot and Zeray districts 
2. Improve capacity of nine Basic Package of Health Services (BPHS) facilities in the identification, treatment and referral of SAM and MAM cases (Maywand: Two Comprehensive Health Centers [CHCs] Khakrez: One CHC Shahwalikot: Two CHCs and one Basic Health Center [BHC] and Zeray: One CHC and two BHCs) 
3. Establishment of breast feeding corners in nine BPHS facilities and 
The proposed four districts are amongst the priority hard to reach districts prioritized for CHF 2nd allocation 2018. 
This project is designed in line with the Nutrition Clusters strategic priorities and will focus on addressing the acute humanitarian needs in these four hard to reach districts. 
The proposed action will target 9,220 direct beneficiaries including 4,587 women and girls. The timeline for the action is from 01 September 2018 until 31 August 2019. Save the Children will implement this project in coordination with all relevant actors at the national, provincial and community levels to ensure effective and timely management of the proposed interventions.</narrative>
  </description>
